# Common operations extension

Package: `com.blockether/vis-common-editing`. Source:
`extensions/common/vis-common-editing/`. Canonical location: inlined
under `[vis :docs \"README.md\"]` in `META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn`
(shipped in the jar). The LLM reads it via
`(meta/extension-readme 'vis)` from inside `:code`.

Filesystem and code-editing primitives the agent reaches for in
nearly every task. Symbols bind under the `vis` alias inside the SCI
sandbox; the underlying namespace alias is `vis.ext.tools`.

Add the jar to the classpath, or list
`com.blockether/vis-common-editing` in your `deps.edn`, to enable
it. The CLI's default `:vis` alias already wires it in for daily
agent runs.

## Read a file

Call: `(vis/cat path)` or `(vis/cat path opts)`. Returns the file
contents along with size and line count. The opts MAP supports paging
for large files; see the symbol's `:examples` for the full form.

```clojure
(vis/cat \"deps.edn\")
(vis/cat \"packages/vis-loop/src/com/blockether/vis/core.clj\"
         {:from-line 1 :to-line 80})
```

## List files and directories

Call: `(vis/ls)` or `(vis/ls path opts)`. Returns a tree projection
trimmed to fit the current context budget; honors `.gitignore` and a
configurable depth/limit.

```clojure
(vis/ls)
(vis/ls \"packages\")
(vis/ls \"extensions\" {:depth 2})
```

## Search files

Call: `(vis/rg pattern)` or `(vis/rg pattern path opts)`. Linear-time
regex search using RE2/J (ReDoS-safe). Returns hits as
`{:path :line :match}` maps. Inside a Clojure string `\\|` is not a
valid escape — use bare `|` for regex alternation, or use a `#\"…\"`
regex literal for complex patterns.

```clojure
(vis/rg \"TODO\")
(vis/rg \"defn\" \"packages/vis-loop/src\")
(vis/rg #\"\\bdef(n|method)\\b\" \"src\")
```

## Patch a file

Call: `(vis/patch edits)`. ONE shape, always: a non-empty vector of
`{:path :search :replace}` maps. Single edit? Vector of one. Multiple
edits in the same file? Multiple maps with the same `:path`. Edits
across files? Multiple maps with different `:path` values. Each entry
contributes one SEARCH/REPLACE block, applied in vector order.

Every map MUST have exactly `:path`, `:search`, `:replace` (all
strings). Extra keys throw a teaching error. `:search` must match the
file contents EXACTLY ONCE — pick the smallest unique snippet;
whitespace and indentation must match the file. Use `:search \"\"` to
insert at the start of a (possibly new) file.

For multi-line content, compose with `(str ...)` so each line stays
on its own physical line and the closing quote stays visible:

```clojure
(vis/patch [{:path \"src/auth.clj\"
             :search  \"(defn login [user]\"
             :replace \"(defn login [user opts]\"}])

(vis/patch [{:path \"src/auth.clj\"
             :search  (str \"(defn login [user]\\n\"
                           \"  (verify user))\")
             :replace (str \"(defn login [user opts]\\n\"
                           \"  (verify user opts))\")}])

(vis/patch [{:path \"src/a.clj\" :search \"x\" :replace \"y\"}
            {:path \"src/b.clj\" :search \"foo\" :replace \"bar\"}])

(vis/patch [{:path \"new.clj\"
             :search  \"\"
             :replace (str \"(ns new)\\n\" \"(def x 1)\\n\")}])
```

When a SEARCH block fails to match exactly, the error includes a
`:near-match` hint when the only difference is leading whitespace, so
you can re-emit a corrected SEARCH block on the next iteration without
re-reading the whole file.

Legacy call shapes (`(vis/patch path search replace)`,
`(vis/patch path marker-text)`, and Codex `*** Begin Patch` payloads)
were removed in favor of this single canonical shape; calling them
throws a teaching error pointing at the canonical example above.

## When to use it

- Reading, listing, searching, or editing files inside the project the
  agent is working on.
- Multi-line or multi-file edits — use ONE `vis/patch` call with a
  vector of edit maps rather than fanning out separate calls.

## When not to use it

- Pure data transformations on already-loaded values; that's plain
  Clojure inside the sandbox.
- Cross-process work that needs a real shell. The extension is
  filesystem-scoped on purpose.

## Implementation notes

- All four symbols are dispatched through the extension framework;
  parse-error rescue lives at the symbol level (e.g. on `vis/rg`) so
  the iteration loop only retries when the broken source actually
  mentions the offending symbol.
- `vis/rg` uses RE2/J (no backtracking, ReDoS-safe). `vis/cat` and
  `vis/ls` are bounded and trim to fit the current context budget.
- `vis/patch` validates the edit vector entirely in memory before any
  disk write — if any entry fails (invalid shape, no SEARCH match,
  ambiguous match), nothing is written and the call throws.
- The extension owns no persistence state. Every call is pure with
  respect to the runtime — the only side effects are file reads and
  the explicit writes performed by `vis/patch`.
